Once upon a TRI... There were 3 little pigs… 📖
—Every triathlete has their unique story. Although, not exactly a fairy tale for me, you could say that building a solid foundation as a triathlete, is similar to that famous fable of the 3 little pigs and the big bad wolf. 
.
The Story. 
🐷🐷🐷: all of us triathletes building upon these foundations:⤵️
.
🌾 (Hay) Easily impulsive w/excitement (some newbies) who are more concern with just the training portion. These athletes are eager to go hard at all 3 sports and expect immediate results. They sadly often end up OVERTRAINED & don’t see what’s coming. That big bad 🐺 wolf will blow💨 them away with the unexpected hurdles (mental & physical) surprises that this sport offers, on training & on race day. They neglected the warning signs and too soon they’re are gone. 
.
🪵 (Sticks) A little stronger. Made of more experienced athletes, who learned from their mistakes, and decide to build a better “base.” They learned that a good plan will include smart training, more recovery & better nutrition. They are aware of the bad wolf 🐺 and want to avoid feeling burn out 🔥. They have potential, but still lacking key powerful (mental) tools to strengthen their fortitude. 
.
🧱 (Brick) A solid foundation. Here you’ll find athletes who by experience & wisdom have reached a level of success. And not just speaking of performance, but a “happy place” where they find longevity + a sense of satisfaction in the sport, despite of a given result from one single race. They know that physical training alone is not enough. They rely & utilize a strong SELF-BELIEVE system. They train intentionally, consistently and with focus on their goals. They know the big bad wolf 🐺 is near (knocking at the door) with emotional discomforts (fear of failure & doubts) but they don’t easily give in & USE mental tools ⚒️ to fight back. These are the ones that stick around & ask for more! 
.
So what foundation style are you building upon? (I’ve been in all 3) #oink 🐷
⛺️🛖🏡 
.

“The real teachable moments come from falling short. Obstacles present decision-pivotal moments that reveal character. Moments that tell us who we really are.” — @richroll 💛
.
My moment: 🏊🏼‍♀️ 
When I signed up for this race (just a few weeks back) I did so with one ☝🏽 goal in mind, which was facing the uncomfortable. Choosing to do the one thing I didn’t want to do all year long. Starting and finishing the open water portion of another triathlon. The goal was to overcome the anxiety that was hijacking my love for the sport and stopping me from signing up for races again (since I had developed some sort of trauma from my previous World’s Championship race, due to a freaky storm while in the water at St George in September of 2021) and have not race since. 
 I had a very short training cycle (5-6 weeks including taper). So of course I wasn’t expecting prs or breakthroughs to impress myself. My biggest motivator was to toe the line and to enter that water. I mentally NEEDED to show up for myself. 🦾
I didn’t know how I would be feeling. There were no  guarantees that I’d have an splendid fast swim. In fact, it was quite the opposite. As it turned out to be my slowest swim of all my races. Despite that, my experience was humbling & beautiful. 🙏🏽
.
I couldn’t put my face down for a long while, not only it was shockingly cold (57 degrees) but I knew that if I was swimming my normal pace it will trigger that panic, so “my decision-pivotal moment” was to swim SLOOOOW in order to stay calm. Having my friend Lia there, racing with me, made a difference. Competition was not the goal on this day. And because of that, it was a challenging character- revealing experience. 
.
Race day brought me confidence again! Despite my 54 cold minutes in that water. This day brought me what I needed it. A time of  learning & growth. These days, nobody wants just that! People want prs and fast impressive moments. For me, this was my WIN! That 1.2 mile in 54 minutes reminding me of who I AM and what I was here for! 💥🤩 
.
{Oh yeah, and there was some biking & running involved to just complete the 70.3 miles. That was just fun!} 😉 #triathlon

Fan-Tan Alley and other fortresses! 🧧🏰
.
My kids will say “Bruh!” —its rough getting back from holidays to regular work hours + school routines?! 😵‍💫
.
Yup! This week reality hits hard, with mom duties and work, plus back to training. But sharing now about a few cool places we visit while in Victoria, Vancouver Island. The FanTan Alley is the narrowest alley in N. America. January gains—Plus understanding HRV (heart rate variability). ⌚️
.
Today I celebrate the month & the start of a much needed recovery week. 
One feature that I’ve been paying close attention to is the HRV in my Garmin, which is determined over the course of 4-5 weeks, based on physical activity, sleep patterns, recovery and overall health of our bodies. As athletes, we want to understand this number.
.
When attempting to figure out what is a good HRV for you, a number of factors such as: 
age, gender, fitness level, lifestyle, and genetics must be taken into account. In other words, it’s an incredibly personalized metric and should not be a source of comparison with your friends ; ) 
If you’re making efforts to better your overall health/fitness, over time you should see your heart rate variability begin to rise. On the other hand, a downward trend in HRV can be a sign that you’re overtraining or simply not getting insufficient sleep (or not enough nutrition) for the demands of training.
 •
“HRV is an indicator of the balance between the activity of the 2 branches of the autonomic nervous system (ANS)—the sympathetic + parasympathetic and therefore it’s an indirect measurement of stress. Higher HRV means lower stress. When the sympathetic branch is more active, your heart rate typically increases, and it beats in more regular rhythm — meaning HRV decreases.” (Garmin) —For example; my HRV is now decreasing (to a 43) as my body is in need of a recovery. But hoping that after a few days it can I bounce back to 45-48). Not sure if it will in 1 week of recovery but the idea is that over time it increases. Phew, all these numbers can easily be confusing. My base is somewhere 48-55). 
•
The important thing is to not get caught up just numbers but to understand them and listen to your body. To FEEL good overall as you progress with training. Often, sleep and nutrition are the two factors that help me balance best, So learn to adjust your load accordingly. 
• 
Do you use this metric? Is it useful to you? 🤔

Race Week {is getting closer & closer} 🏁 Ahh! 📣
.
And no worries, “that’s” just a bad case of the taper tantrums!! 😵‍💫
.
Taper tantrums? Yeah that’s a thing. Simply —It’s the psychological effect on athletes from a reduction of training volume. And as runners enter this last week before Boston, we’re probably experiencing some (or all) of the following symptoms. 
.
❎ a little antsy, moody and/or sluggish.
❎ a random ache or pain in your body. 
❎ a sense of hyperactivity or brain fog.
❎ a few nightmares/random race dreams. 
❎ a sudden desire/urge to sign up for a another race (the harder the better)🤔🙋🏻‍♀️😂
.
Hey 👋🏽—Don’t panic. To help cope til race day, here are some strategies: 
.
🚩 A flowy mobility/yoga session.
🚩 A calming Epson salt bath (w/classic/soft music or hard metal whatever is soothing to you). 
🚩A short walk with your dog/kids to the park. 
🚩 A written race plan + reminder in your phone/notes to TRUST your training. 
🚩 A quick trip to Red light/ Cryo Therapy. 
🚩 A distraction at home (de clutter a junk drawer  or organize your closet). 
🚩 A list of race items (packing) + finding old clothes you can donate and use on race morning. 
🚩 A favorite Netflix binge but easy on the popcorn. 
🚩 A new race playlist. 
As you can see, it’s ALL about keeping your brain 🧠 active and distracted from the fact that you are not training hard anymore. Your mind can work in your favor or against you. But you are smart and you GOT THIS!
.
Now, let’s keep it together! Shall we?! 😂

Medal Monday! Posting cause it’s such a pretty & colorful medal! Don’t you think? ☀️

I haven’t race a stand alone half marathon in a while. Last time I did it was the Nebo half two years ago. And even tho Saturday wasn’t a Half Pr it was my second fastest (1:49) and made me happy cause im also 2 years older 😂 and the course wasn’t as steep downhill which made it an honest slower course.

My first three miles were a little rough. I knew I had to take it easy and I had to hold back a little since the first part of the race is all gradual downhill. But I couldn’t find a good rhythm until like mile 4-5. Then I had to switch my mind game. I told myself “just because you don’t feel great right now, it doesn’t mean you won’t feel better later” haha 😂 which is funny cause everyone that races KNOWS that is usually it gets harder, but also proof that you don’t ever want to take yourself out til the race it’s actually over. 

I loved the course and loved the experience. There were over 2000 runners doing the half, and in my AG about 89. Taking 4th was a challenge, definitely some speed demons  out there! 😂
My goal was to pace it about (1:55)  8:35/8:40 and actually was a slighter faster than that with a 8:20-22 pace overall! 💥The negative split was a huge Bonus since the last 7 miles were a long flat road that felt like an eternity. Especially hard when you had to keep increasing your speed. Last three miles were speedy (for me) average 8:02 and sprint to the end! It was “SO FUN” (7:27 pace ) 🥵😂

Overall, grateful to race again and for giving it an honest hard push! Also glad it wasn’t a full marathon this time! 😂

Thank you @runutahvalley for an amazing event and all the great volunteers. Plus thanks to everyone for all the support and well wishes. I “should” retire now… Or NOT! 😂

If you’ve lived this life, you’ll know it hasn’t been an easy one. But —along the hardest things I’ve  experienced, I’ve also gain a perspective that many in this country will never understand. 
Most of those hard things are not even related to physically fitness —that’s been the easy part for me —in comparison to real life struggles. Many of you can relate, right?! 

So —Why are we  expected to do only “hard things in training” to prove something to anyone?! 

I often ponder on this question as we live in a culture of: 
1 . Go big or go home. 
2. You can do hard things 
3. The harder you go the bigger the reward.
4. Go hard (or else) —maybe you are not cool enough or something?! 😂

Lucky for me, I can choose to take absolutely everything easy in my life from now on if I want to. 🤣  I’ve done A LOT of the HARD (during my childhood and teenage years and into my twenties). I can do the easy part now. The “play time” part. And yet, real hard life can still happen any given day. 

A bunch of races to challenge my stamina and muscles. A bunch of events to interact with other athletes. Marathons, ultras, ironmans + other events. It has been all for fun, people. It’s meant to be a hobby, not a career and (although is a lifestyle) is meant to keep my brain and body healthy and working well, not kill myself deteriorating it. 
Longevity is far more valuable and exciting to me! So take it easy, if you want to! 💥

I giggle when people keep sharing how “hard” a race or workout is or it was. Well of course (a challenge) and you CHOSE it “for fun” (cause unless you are a pro you don’t have to). 
Also if you  believe you were capable of doing that’s great, to push yourself. So you win! 
So that’s a good thing to have for fun. Right?! So stop complaining. And start enjoying it! 

Hard things often times are out of our control like a mental illness, or losing a love one, or parenthood in general, or working overtime to provide for a family, or growing up in a third world country, or immigrating and facing cultural, race, religious differences and rejection. 
Let’s keep encouraging and inspiring to do THE fun! True hard things come our way despite our choosing anyways! ✌🏽😃

You showing up to do the work on your own. When and where is convenient. Motivation or no motivation. Rain or shine. Early or late. Close or far. 
You know you can’t rely on others to do this for you. And you must say no more than once in order to stay as close to your daily/ monthly goals as possible.

You glow different when you remember that: 👉🏽 You are NOT like ANYONE else! ✨✨✨

✨ Every so often I tell myself this ☝🏽 truth. It takes me to a higher place. Not to look down on others, but instead, to look deeper inside and admire the person I’m becoming and the growth that has occurred.

 ✨ In this world of comparison & competitiveness, where material possessions, social status, tittles, over-achievements and desperate need to “fit” into x-y-z (you fill in that blank), is refreshing to KNOW who you are. And to think of ALL THE GOOD you have to offer. 
To know you are of great worth. To know you can love yourself NOW —as you are.

1️⃣0️⃣ YEAR special edition Medal Monday @ IM Washington 70.3! 
💥🎉

Ten years on the making. I don’t know how long is the live span of most triathletes racing 3 years? 5 years? 20? Just humbled for all these years! 🤷🏻‍♀️

I’m a stronger person today than 10 years ago because of this sport. What I learned in all these years is that nothing is guaranteed on a single race. That progress isn’t linear. That when you race you are closer to GOD and he adds a measure of strength when you feel you can’t go any longer. That you don’t do this alone unless you have a solid support crew. That you must  show up with grit, courage & confidence to succeed. That when you believe, work and ask, than anything is possible! 

Goals: 
1️⃣ Swim Free of Fear! ✔️ 
I’ve always struggled with open water anxiety. Something about 100’s (more) of people throwing arms and kicks and making a huge bubble washing machine that just doesn’t sit well with me. I swam with peace & confidence and had my lowest HR EVER than any other swims. —Mission accomplished! 
2️⃣ Bike strong but relax! ✔️
My goal wasn’t to race this super fast. I held back and it paid off as I felt so relaxed and despite decent elevation gain with lots of technical hills (with turns at every corner 3,050ft)  I crushed it by feeling chilled on each climb. Passed so many dudes 😂 —Mission accomplished! 
3️⃣ Run this smart & break a 2 hours: 
Breaking this 2 hours has been the hardest thing for me on an Ironman race. Is like at mile 9-10 I’m just dead. My friend who races this before, warned me this wasn’t a pr course. I ran conservatively but steady and had to incorporate 30’s strides. I had to dig so deep to actual make it. I wanted this bad. The last hill almost crushed my goal. This unusual trail run wasn’t easy and many were walking giving me the false signal to just walk. But I had to ignore the intense temptation. 1:58 —Mission accomplished! 

My heart is full ♥️ from racing this gorgeous green course! 
Streak #14 IM70.3 races with no DNFs. That’s almost unheard of. 
Thank you for letting me share my story. Is one of never stop believing & working on your goals! 🙏🏽

Make it a habit: FINISH STRONG!💥

Nothing feels better (mentally 🤭) than arriving to the run portion of an Ironman(full or half distances). Is like you know you did 2/3 of that race and victory is close. 
Only to have your body revolt against you within minutes, to reminds you of the pain you’re about to feel. {Insert here evil laughter 😈 aka: the run of a Tri}. 
 I wanted to stay focused on my goal (sub 2h) but I knew it would be fierce fight 
to achieve & important to pace it right. The course was a gravel-false flat but so green (arboretum) with a few river crossings. 🌲
As expected, at this point (5 hours into non-stop physical effort) I knew my body battery 🪫 was pretty low. Staying on top of calories-sodium is crucial. Nailed it. I told myself on the bike several times “the run wins the race” so I intentionally held back from pushing 18-19 mph average pace. maybe I’d have gained 5-10 minutes on the bike; trashed my legs good and then would have lost 15-25+ minutes on a slower run-walk. So glad I didn’t do that. 

Learning to race a triathlon as ONE sport (takes time & experience). I’ve made mistakes in the past & kept learning the hard way, but you gotta respect the science and wisdom of this sport.

The first 3-4 miles I felt comfortable. I stay relax & steady. A much younger dude (early 30’s) said to me, how are you running so relax, steady, happy? -while I’m here dying and walking? — to what I quickly & smiley responded: you got this friend, it’s best if you enjoy it and ease into the run, relax and enjoy the views, focus on nutrition now so you can CRUSH it on the last 4 miles (when the race starts) hence finish STRONG like a champ! 
He smiled and yelled (as I continue to pass him) Hey, today you are my hero!! 🦸🏻‍♀️🦸 ;) 

I hope he was able to finish strong. For me pushing e/mile harder to the finish was so painful, but I did it smart. Everything in my body was begging me to walk. I came to the finish and claimed my sub 2hour (at 1:58). It landed me a 7th place in the run and a TOP 10th place AG —YES!! 💥All the feels at the finish line 🏁 with at 10/10 pain level and 1000% satisfied with a solid effort. 🏆  @athletes.lgmphotos 📸

Trails often promotes pondering. We think more clearly and more creatively when we surround ourselves in nature m, at least for a little while. But today while I was on the trails I thought of something that lately has been on my mind.
Something profound about OUR human NATURE! Something I learned from an old Hindú tale: About an old monk trying to save a scorpion from drowning in a pond, by trying to take it out of the water multiple times,  despite the scorpion biting him every time. Another monk asked him “Why are you trying to save this scorpion?  He keeps on biting you every time you try and it’s not that deserving!” — The first monk responded: “It’s not in his nature to be grateful or show kindness. — It is in my NATURE to help him survive.” 

We DO NOT need to change our good nature in order to fit in, to be cool, to be liked, or to be more popular. Especially if our intentions are good and genuine. We are who we are. It is in us or it isn’t. 
Yes, we can improve and learn to become BETTER. Each day we can practice and enhance our good nature. But when others reject us or don’t show appreciation, kindness or respect in response to our good nature. Let it be their doing to be like that, not yours. 💛

Our nature (our actual authenticity) is the essence of our purpose in life. That doesn’t depend on anyone else, but us. Just like nature is beautiful to the ones that notice it, and to the ones that don’t.

Who we are (our genuine tendencies) the ones that drives you to GIVE more without expectations, to FORGIVE more, to SMILE more, to show more COMPASSION for others, to be more INCLUSIVE, and to be more HOPEFUL, is literally what we are made of.

The GSP {the goal setting process}. 
2•0•2•4 —Got Goals?! 🔍

My approach on setting goals at the beginning of the year, is more of a thorough-reflection-process than a task of wishful thinking. 💫

🔎 First. I look back by asking myself these  thought-provoking questions:

~ What worked and what didn’t in 2023?
~ What, where & who brought me joy or lack of it? 
~ What needs change? 
~ What areas need improvement? 
~ What habits did or didn’t serve me well? 
Doing this step first, helps us recognize weaknesses and strengths & provide us with direction to AIM higher. 💫

Digging deep in order to bring to light: 
💡 any negative or positive feelings associated with a place, an activity or a particular person, that brought us fulfillment personal growth or caused us discomfort, disappointment or even pain. 
 
🔎 Second. I must set honest intentions. What is the purpose of that goal? What principle or attribute I’m hoping to attain from this new resolutions?
Thinking of a WORD that remind us throughout the week, month, and year, has a powerful effect on our mind. 🧿

💡Once I have these questions answered (feelings & intentions) then I’m more ready to prepare an actionable plan of 
CONSISTENCY. 
(The goal in any goal, is to master consistency). 

A well-thought of 💭 process takes time & effort at first. But it’s easier & more EFFECTIVE to follow when the steps have been aligned & identified in your brain 🧠 and in your heart. ♥️
